title: The Statistical Methods Ontology
description: STATO is a general-purpose STATistics Ontology. Its aim is to provide coverage for processes such as statistical tests, their conditions of application, and information needed or resulting from statistical methods, such as probability distributions, variables, spread and variation metrics. STATO also covers aspects of experimental design and description of plots and graphical representations commonly used to provide visual cues of data distribution or layout and to assist review of the results.
repo_description: This is the development repository for the STATistics Ontology (STATO). For more information and demonstration on the ontology content, please visit its website:

title: Software ontology
description: The Software Ontology (SWO) is a resource for describing software tools, their types, tasks, versions, provenance and associated data. It contains detailed information on licensing and formats as well as software applications themselves, mainly (but not limited) to the bioinformatics community.
repo_description: The Software Ontology (SWO) is a resource for describing software tools, their types, tasks, versions, licences, provenance and associated data.

title: Symptom Ontology
description: An ontology of disease symptoms, with symptoms encompasing perceived changes in function, sensations or appearance reported by a patient indicative of a disease.
repo_description: The symptom ontology was designed around the guiding concept of a symptom being: “A perceived change in function, sensation or appearance reported by a patient indicative of a disease”. Understanding the close relationship of Signs and Symptoms, where Signs are the objective observation of an illness, the Symptom Ontology will work to broaden it’s scope to capture and document in a more robust manor these two sets of terms. Understanding that at times, the same term may be both a Sign and a Symptom.  The Symptom Ontology is available under CC0 license (https://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/).

repo_description: The Pathogen Transmission Ontology describes the tranmission methods of human disease pathogens describing how a pathogen is transmitted from one host, reservoir, or source to another host. The pathogen transmission may occur either directly or indirectly and may involve animate vectors or inanimate vehicles. The Pathogen Transmission Ontology is available under CC0 license (https://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/).
